HTML  -- hyper text markup language.

HTML headings are defined with the <h1> to <h6> tags.

<h1> defines the most important heading. <h6> defines the least important heading.

<h1>Heading 1</h1>
<h2>Heading 2</h2>
<h3>Heading 3</h3>
<h4>Heading 4</h4>
<h5>Heading 5</h5>
<h6>Heading 6</h6>

<br> is for break the lines.
<hr> is for draw the horizontal line.
<hr size="3" noshade> is for size of line and its thickness.
<!--  ........   --!>   is for comment the html lines.
<p>  paragraph tag to write paragraph tag.
<em> for italic font.
<strong> to bold the tags.

<ul> unordered list.
ol is a ordered list
li is the list items.
In ul bydefault sign is a disc.

<ol type="1">
      <li>first item</li>
      <li>second item</li>
      <li>third line</li>
</ol>

<ul type="circle">
      <li>first item</li>
      <li>second item</li>
      <li>third line</li>
</ul>

<ul>	Defines an unordered list
<ol>	Defines an ordered list
<li>	Defines a list item
<dl>	Defines a description list
<dt>	Defines a term in a description list
<dd>	Describes the term in a description list

<dl>
  <dt>Coffee</dt>
  <dd>- black hot drink</dd>
  <dt>Milk</dt>
  <dd>- white cold drink</dd>
</dl>

Use the <a> element to define a link
Use the href attribute to define the link address
Use the target attribute to define where to open the linked document
Use the <img> element (inside <a>) to use an image as a link
Use the mailto: scheme inside the href attribute to create a link that opens the user's email program



